The Seventy-First Regiment Armory, Broadway, east side, from 35th to 36th Streets.

About 1890.

Broadway, east side, north from West 35th Street (Right) showing prominently the newly erected Herald Building. This replaced the old 71st Inf. Regiment Armory. Note the absence of the tri-figured "Bell Ringers" that was mounted in 1895 atop the Herald Building.
About 1893-4
H. N. Tiemann, photo
Gift of Urbrock Collection

Broadway, west side, from West 35th to 36th Street's, showing prominently the Herald Square Theatre. This is at the N.W. corner of 35th Street. It was first opened in 1883 as the New Park. Later Harrigan took a lease and produced "O1d Lavender","Fate" and other successes. The name was changed to that shown in 1895. The following year Belasco's play "The Heart of Maryland" was produced here. Lew Fields was the final lessee. The house
was torn down in 1912.

At the left and right margins respectively appear Macy's Department Store and the Hotel Marlborough. Slightly to the right of the former is the Arsenal tower at Seventh Ave.

About 1910

Broadway, east side, from 37th to 35th Streets. The left building nearing completion has replaced four two- and four-story The Sheridan Building and the corner building at 36th Street been demolished, and the Greenwich Savings Bank is under construction

Broadway, east side, north from Weat 35th Street. It is at this point (34th Street), that Broadway intersects Sixth Ave. A Broadway Street Car is shown in the foreground. Building under construction is the new Rogers Peet and Company Building on 36th Street, between Broadway
and Sixth Ave.
April 1929.
Eugene L. Armbruster, Collection.
